Novelty &amp; Significance of the Proposed CFD\'96Koopman\'96HHL Pipeline\
Overview: The proposed pipeline integrates geometry-aware design innovation with\
advanced physics modeling. It couples generative car-body design via constructive solid\
geometry (CSG), a Koopman operator (DMD/EDMD) flow linearization, and a quantum-\
inspired solver (HHL). We assess its novelty against existing work in four key areas: (a)\
automotive CFD surrogates, (b) Koopman/DMD for aerodynamics, (c) quantum linear solvers\
for CFD, and (d) steady\'96transient data fusion.\
(a) Automotive CFD Surrogates: Novelty vs Prior Work\
\uc0\u61623  **Prior Art: Data-driven aerodynamic surrogates are well-established. For instance, the\
DrivAerNet and DrivAerNet++ projects (MIT, 2024\'9625) provide thousands of\
parameterized car shapes with CFD-derived drag and lift (fastback, notchback, etc.) for\
training ML predictive models. Additionally, generative and surrogate modeling\
workflows (e.g., MIT\'92s DeCoDe Lab, 2023 study) have explored deep learning to\
predict car drag for thousands of shapes to guide design. However, these efforts\
largely remain within parametric or shape database boundaries (e.g., resizing,\
small variations of existing shapes). [arxiv.org] [decode.mit.edu], [decode.mit.edu]\
[decode.mit.edu]\
\uc0\u61623  **Proposed Pipeline\'92s Novelty: Expanding the design search beyond known\
topologies. The pipeline applies a CSG-based \'93topology search\'94 to create\
fundamentally new car body shapes beyond the standard parametric design space. This\
approach addresses the \'93topology gap\'94 \'96 the inability of parametric design to explore\
radically different geometries. No known prior automotive aerodynamics study has used\
CSG with a Catalan grammar to generate diverse topologies (adding/subtracting body\
parts) and then optimize them, making this a first-of-kind integration. The pipeline also\
reuses an existing graph neural-network surrogate (from prior work, \'93Paper 1\'94, on a\
different domain) for rapid performance evaluation of thousands of designs. In summary,\
the synergy of CSG-based shape synthesis plus AI surrogate for aerodynamic\
performance is a novel step forward. [Paper3_Aut..._HHL_Scope | Txt]\
(b) Koopman/DMD in Aerodynamic Flow Modeling: Novelty vs Prior Work\
\uc0\u61623  Prior Art: Dynamic Mode Decomposition (DMD) and its extended Koopman-operator\
variants are widely used in fluid dynamics research to extract coherent flow structures\
and oscillation frequencies. For example, Ahani &amp; Uddin (2025) applied DMD to the\
classic Ahmed body (simplified car shape) at Re ~7.7\'d710^5, isolating wake modes in\
distinct frequency ranges (Strouhal St \uc0\u8776  0.07 for \'93bubble pumping\'94 and ~0.13\'960.17 for\
vortex shedding). These analysis-focused studies, however, are typically limited to\
understanding one fixed geometry\'92s flow behavior, not to rapid evaluation of many\
design candidates. [mdpi.com] [mdpi.com], [mdpi.com]\
\uc0\u61623  Proposed Pipeline\'92s Novelty: Using Koopman operator methods as a design\
surrogate for aerodynamic evaluation in near real-time. The pipeline\'92s EDMD-based\
Koopman linearization is employed to transform nonlinear aerodynamics around a given\
\
shape into a linear system (A\'b7x = b), enabling fast solution. While Koopman/DMD itself\
is established in aerodynamics research, embedding it into a multi-design\
optimization loop is new. The pipeline\'92s idea is to leverage DMD/Koopman not just for\
understanding one flow, but to help accelerate predicting performance (Cd, Cl) for\
multiple shapes. This is a creative reuse of DMD: from analysis tool to surrogate\
model mechanism. A key challenge here is ensuring the method works for turbulent\
automotive flows \'96 which the pipeline plans to address via careful selection of\
Koopman observables and a validation on simpler flows (e.g., the Ahmed body wake)\
before scaling up. [Paper3_Aut..._HHL_Scope | Txt], [Paper3_Aut..._HHL_Scope | Txt]\
(c) Quantum Linear Solvers for CFD: Novelty vs Prior Work\
\uc0\u61623  Prior Art: The concept of applying Harrow\'96Hassidim\'96Lloyd (HHL) or related quantum\
linear solvers to fluid simulation has been broached in recent research. Ye et al.\
(Physics of Fluids, 2024) introduced a hybrid quantum-classical CFD framework,\
transforming fluid equations into linear systems and solving via HHL and variational\
quantum linear solvers (VQLS) with promising accuracy (\uc0\u8764 0.1% error) on unsteady\
cylinder flows and turbulence around an aircraft. Their approach used subspace\
reduction to handle large linear systems (simulating up to ~9.4 million grid cells) on\
limited quantum resources. Moreover, companies like Quanscient (2026) have\
demonstrated a 15-step quantum Lattice Boltzmann simulation with an obstacle on\
real quantum hardware, heralded as \'93one of the most realistic quantum CFD\
simulations to date\'94. However, these efforts are at an early conceptual stage \'96\
quantum speedups in CFD remain theoretical until larger fault-tolerant quantum\
computers are available. [pubs.aip.org] [thequantum...nsider.com],\
[thequantum...nsider.com]\
\uc0\u61623  Proposed Pipeline\'92s Novelty: First integration of a quantum-solver concept into an\
aerodynamic design pipeline. The novelty here is one of \'93visionary synthesis\'94 rather\
than immediate technical discovery. No prior system links generative car design\
with a quantum-ready flow solver, so the pipeline is breaking new ground by\
presenting CFD\'96quantum integration as a future-ready concept. It is a forward-looking\
novelty: practically, the pipeline will simulate HHL on classical hardware (to validate\
correctness and quantify speed-up potential). The results will be framed as \'93quantum-\
ready\'94 rather than delivering real-time quantum advantage today. This is an unusual but\
innovative coupling \'96 effectively anticipating quantum computing\'92s maturation by\
designing a workflow that could exploit it when available. The challenge is to avoid\
overpromising: HHL\'92s exponential speedup requires well-conditioned matrices (\uc0\u954  &lt;&lt;\
1000), so for realistic turbulent flows (which might have high \uc0\u954 ) the advantage may be\
small. Top-tier journals will recognize the bold integration and demonstration of\
HHL for automotive flows as novel, but they will also expect transparent caveats\
around the quantum component\'92s practical limits. [Paper3_Aut..._HHL_Scope | Txt]\
(d) Steady vs Transient Data Fusion: Novelty vs Prior Work\
\uc0\u61623  Prior Art: Hybridizing different fidelity data for aerodynamic models is an emerging\
trend. Multi-fidelity surrogate frameworks combine cheaper, lower-fidelity models\
with expensive high-fidelity simulations to improve predictions under limited data\
budgets. For example, Yang et al. (2026) developed a multi-fidelity surrogate for UAV\
aerodynamics that mixes panel-method (fast, low accuracy) with RANS (slow, high\
accuracy) data via transfer learning. However, these methods primarily merge steady-\
state data of varying fidelity and seldom (if ever) consider mixing steady vs transient\
flow datasets in one model. The typical assumption is that training data must be\
\
consistently defined (all steady or all unsteady) or physically similar. [mdpi.com],\
[mdpi.com] [mdpi.com]\
\uc0\u61623  Proposed Pipeline\'92s Novelty: Combining a broad steady-state dataset with targeted\
transient data to enhance model fidelity. The pipeline merges DrivAerNet++\'92s steady\
RANS snapshots (for thousands of shapes) with transient flows (e.g., Ahmed body\
wakes) to inform the Koopman operator linearization about time-dependent\
aerodynamics. This strategy is fairly novel: to our knowledge, no published surrogate\
or reduced-order model explicitly fuses static and dynamic CFD data in this manner. In\
practice, the pipeline\'92s approach uses transient flows to tune and validate the\
EDMD/Koopman model (ensuring it captures known vortex-shedding patterns\'97like\
the Von K\'e1rm\'e1n street and Strouhal ~0.2 in bluff-body flows). Meanwhile, the large\
steady dataset provides the geometric diversity needed for generalization. This hybrid\
training approach (steady shapes + unsteady physics) is a creative solution to data\
limitations (since DrivAerNet++ itself may lack fully time-resolved data). A potential\
limitation is that RANS \'93snapshots\'94 are not true unsteady flows\'97so to apply EDMD\
meaningfully, the team may need to generate unsteady CFD for a subset of designs\
(increasing cost). Nevertheless, the concept of injecting real transient physics into a\
design surrogate adds a physics-grounded layer that sets this pipeline apart from\
purely data-driven surrogates.}